1
00:00:01,330 --> 00:00:18,562
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambhudasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambhudasa

2
00:00:18,542 --> 00:00:33,436
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:33,457 --> 00:00:34,560
Now,

4
00:00:34,810 --> 00:00:40,335
Yesterday I gave the moon talk and then it failed to, well, I failed to do the right thing.

5
00:00:40,414 --> 00:00:41,235
And so I lost it.

6
00:00:41,756 --> 00:00:43,438
So I'm doing it again.

7
00:00:43,457 --> 00:00:55,448
I'll be covering exactly the same ground, but of course it won't be quite the same as you yourself had heard it, or as those on the moon broadcast had heard it.

8
00:00:56,409 --> 00:01:03,957
So we're talking about the dependent origination and centering towards the end on this process of desiring.

9
00:01:06,046 --> 00:01:17,643
Now, the depeneration begins with this word avidya, and it's been translated as ignorance, giving it some sort of culpability, you know, like we shouldn't have been ignorant.

10
00:01:17,783 --> 00:01:22,028
But no, this is just a plain flat not knowing, didn't know.

11
00:01:22,069 --> 00:01:25,915
And it's because of that that we fall into a delusion.

12
00:01:26,695 --> 00:01:35,108
And that delusion, of course, is to believe ourselves to be this heart, body, and mind, this psychophysical organism.

13
00:01:35,441 --> 00:01:40,510
And that leads us into a funny relationship with the world, wanting to be happy.

14
00:01:41,150 --> 00:01:45,096
So we acquire things, money, friends, power, and so on.

15
00:01:45,658 --> 00:01:51,768
And then anything that upsets us or threatens us, we push away, we get angry and so on.

16
00:01:52,448 --> 00:01:56,355
And if it's bigger than me, then of course I'll run for it.

17
00:01:56,375 --> 00:02:01,162
So these are your basic attitudes that come from that delusion.

18
00:02:01,885 --> 00:02:03,566
Inquisitiveness, aversion and fear.

19
00:02:04,067 --> 00:02:07,512
And they have created these sankara.

20
00:02:07,533 --> 00:02:12,258
The sankara is translated rather awkwardly as volitional conditioning.

21
00:02:12,919 --> 00:02:22,171
But I think it's much easier to think of them just as our habits, habits of thought, habits of feeling, habits of reaction and so on.

22
00:02:24,025 --> 00:02:35,158
And these two, this not knowing, this delusion, and the sankara, the habits, underlie every moment of our life.

23
00:02:35,179 --> 00:02:37,701
They're just passing with us underneath every moment.

24
00:02:38,824 --> 00:02:46,252
Now, when something moves on the sankara, it will manifest on that screen of consciousness.

25
00:02:46,671 --> 00:03:02,153
And consciousness is described by its six bases, the five sensual bases, the eye, ear, nose, and so on, and the mind-heart, the inner life of images, thoughts, emotions.

26
00:03:03,616 --> 00:03:12,949
And these five consciousnesses, whenever there's a stimulus, it'll manifest on that screen.

27
00:03:14,937 --> 00:03:26,871
Now then we have, because of that screen, we of course become aware of our body and mind, of our materiality and of our mentality.

28
00:03:27,471 --> 00:03:36,221
And it can also be understood as what is subjective mentality and what is objective, our physicality.

29
00:03:37,362 --> 00:03:44,691
And these physical, psychophysical organism has of course these six sense bases.

30
00:03:45,245 --> 00:04:00,526
And whenever we have a contact, which includes a sense base, some sort of object, and the awareness, the consciousness of it, we have that moment when we become aware of something, conscious of something.

31
00:04:02,689 --> 00:04:08,538
Now, that moment is, shall we say, just an experience.

32
00:04:08,558 --> 00:04:14,086
But we then put a judgment on it.

33
00:04:14,590 --> 00:04:19,343
or we look at it from the point of view of happiness.

34
00:04:19,744 --> 00:04:24,297
So obviously, there are some things that make us happy and some things that don't.

35
00:04:25,178 --> 00:04:29,511
And that's the point where it becomes vedana, or feeling.

36
00:04:29,845 --> 00:04:33,009
physical feelings, mental feelings.

37
00:04:33,069 --> 00:04:46,625
So as soon as these first little sensations come up in our sitting posture, for instance, of pain in the knee or pain in the back or pain in the neck, as soon as they come up, immediately we say, oh, that's pain.

38
00:04:47,086 --> 00:04:48,788
Pain meaning don't like.

39
00:04:50,410 --> 00:04:56,798
And of course, if it's something pleasant, we suddenly have a lovely, joyous memory, then of course,

40
00:04:57,233 --> 00:05:00,661
We label that as something to be enjoyed.

41
00:05:02,386 --> 00:05:06,677
It's the point next, which is the problem, how we relate to it.

42
00:05:07,278 --> 00:05:09,223
And this is our reactivity.

43
00:05:10,526 --> 00:05:13,875
So because we've determined to try to make this life

44
00:05:13,973 --> 00:05:15,593
really absolutely happy.

45
00:05:16,074 --> 00:05:22,439
Whenever something does create happiness, we grasp it, we try to maintain it, we try to make it grow.

46
00:05:23,240 --> 00:05:27,343
And when something is unpleasant, we want to push it away, etc.

47
00:05:28,444 --> 00:05:35,610
That's the point of this tanha, this translated as craving, but that's too strong.

48
00:05:35,790 --> 00:05:43,557
Thirst is not bad, but it's just that reactivity coming from the wrong understanding.

49
00:05:44,634 --> 00:05:47,639
Now, at the next point, there is an identity.

50
00:05:48,721 --> 00:05:54,331
And this is the point where actually suffering begins, because that's when you say, this is me.

51
00:05:54,672 --> 00:05:56,875
I am this pain in the knee.

52
00:05:57,297 --> 00:05:58,319
I am depressed.

53
00:05:59,841 --> 00:06:07,875
And once that is determined, it's virtually impossible to stop the empowerment of that desire.

54
00:06:08,968 --> 00:06:21,483
So if the desire said, take an aspirin, get rid of this headache, and you say, yes, I will take an aspirin to get rid of it, it's virtually impossible to stop reaching out for the aspirin.

55
00:06:21,843 --> 00:06:29,773
You may, of course, change your mind in the process, but the reaching out or the movement towards, even the slightest movement, will be very difficult to stop.

56
00:06:31,454 --> 00:06:38,182
And then once you've started an action, there'll be a process of the action and the completion of the action, right?

57
00:06:38,668 --> 00:06:45,920
Now that's looking at dependence origination from a present moment to moment experience.

58
00:06:45,939 --> 00:06:50,726
But of course it is also explained as a sort of three lives.

59
00:06:51,728 --> 00:06:55,033
In the past life, we've developed these habits.

60
00:06:55,173 --> 00:06:58,898
We come into this life with consciousness, with awareness.

61
00:06:59,439 --> 00:07:00,860
We go through this process.

62
00:07:01,422 --> 00:07:04,086
We build up, hopefully better,

63
00:07:04,403 --> 00:07:07,749
habits, which get us reborn in a better place.

64
00:07:08,209 --> 00:07:12,016
And life begins again, birth, death, birth, death.

65
00:07:12,377 --> 00:07:28,706
But to us, I think as, well, what can we say as, as Westerners really much more involved in our psychology and all that, then the moment to moment changes.

66
00:07:29,699 --> 00:07:36,675
or the present moment experience of Dependent Origination makes much more sense to us.

67
00:07:36,716 --> 00:07:44,535
Now, this is what's really important here is the Buddha's tremendous insight about the point of

68
00:07:45,324 --> 00:07:46,586
in identity.

69
00:07:47,427 --> 00:07:58,182
So if we take a very simple sentence, which some of you will have heard me often use, one sees ice cream, one makes a contact with ice cream.

70
00:07:58,744 --> 00:08:06,093
It's a lovely sunny day, it's very warm, you're out walking and there it is, the vision, the seeing of the ice cream.

71
00:08:06,935 --> 00:08:11,502
And immediately that brings up a sense of liking.

72
00:08:11,666 --> 00:08:15,651
Once you like something, there's a wanting, right?

73
00:08:15,670 --> 00:08:18,093
So there's a contact, I scream.

74
00:08:18,774 --> 00:08:21,295
There's like, I scream.

75
00:08:21,656 --> 00:08:23,737
There's want, I scream.

76
00:08:23,997 --> 00:08:27,021
And then there's I want, I scream.

77
00:08:27,762 --> 00:08:30,363
So the I comes in late in the process.

78
00:08:31,365 --> 00:08:33,126
I is a sense of identity.

79
00:08:33,167 --> 00:08:35,068
This is me.

80
00:08:35,089 --> 00:08:38,552
If that weren't so, there wouldn't be an escape.

81
00:08:38,802 --> 00:08:39,926
there wouldn't be an escape.

82
00:08:40,287 --> 00:08:51,023
It's the fact that it comes at the end of that process, that we can now, instead of moving into that identity, actually stop at the point of desire.

83
00:08:52,386 --> 00:08:57,215
And when we stop at the point of desire, we can see that process quite clearly.

84
00:08:57,816 --> 00:09:06,870
It's a sort of energy that wants to manifest, and it needs our permission, a decision to manifest.

85
00:09:07,370 --> 00:09:08,893
And that's what comes after

86
00:09:08,873 --> 00:09:12,523
This identity is known as bhava, becoming.

87
00:09:13,024 --> 00:09:22,831
When we are becoming, we are creating a self all the time, but it's also an action and therefore there are consequences.

88
00:09:23,706 --> 00:09:26,532
and it all reverts back to this desire.

89
00:09:26,873 --> 00:09:34,405
Now, we're talking here specifically about unwholesome desire, but it also works for wholesome desires.

90
00:09:34,787 --> 00:09:39,235
Now, unlike the Buddha, we have this underlying

91
00:09:40,429 --> 00:09:54,490
identity we have this underlying delusion and so no matter how we try there'll always be that sense of self now that doesn't mean to say it um it somehow uh

92
00:09:54,688 --> 00:10:14,773
destroys the benefit of a good action far from it but there'll always be that sense of me doing something and with it this on this underlying little conversation about how wonderful we are or how we're not so wonderful or how we've given too much spent too much and so on and so forth yeah

93
00:10:16,423 --> 00:10:23,673
So now if we go back to this desire, we have to feel that, okay?

94
00:10:23,692 --> 00:10:34,485
So in our meditation, when we're sitting there, as soon as something comes into our attention, on that screen of consciousness, we become aware of it, right?

95
00:10:34,927 --> 00:10:43,798
As soon as that happens, the Mahasi technique of labeling is extremely good at making us acknowledge what is happening.

96
00:10:44,554 --> 00:10:50,203
So if my mind is wandering, I know wandering, but then I can see that I'm planning something.

97
00:10:50,705 --> 00:10:51,866
So I know planning.

98
00:10:51,927 --> 00:11:01,202
And when I come back into the body, I can feel the agitation, the excitement of this amazing thing that I'm going to do, saving the world.

99
00:11:01,243 --> 00:11:10,477
And if I can stay with that, I'll see that there's a sort of little energy that wants to take me out, take me back into the dream world.

100
00:11:12,128 --> 00:11:13,710
And I've got to be aware of that.

101
00:11:14,331 --> 00:11:21,822
If there's an iota, a moment of inattention, I'll shoot off again up into la-la land.

102
00:11:23,703 --> 00:11:31,115
So this whole process is explained by the Buddha in this dependent origination.

103
00:11:32,356 --> 00:11:35,140
And this desire has to be felt.

104
00:11:35,620 --> 00:11:36,602
It has to be known.

105
00:11:37,043 --> 00:11:38,946
It has to be understood.

106
00:11:39,466 --> 00:11:44,934
So that when the desire comes and we see it is unwholesome, we've got to hold it there.

107
00:11:44,955 --> 00:11:45,856
We've got to stand.

108
00:11:46,336 --> 00:11:47,899
We mustn't let it take us.

109
00:11:48,240 --> 00:11:55,111
We mustn't let it tempt us into an action, a thought, word or deed.

110
00:11:55,091 --> 00:11:57,357
And if we fail, that's not a problem.

111
00:11:57,558 --> 00:12:01,308
You just know that, ah, yeah, it's still a very strong habit.

112
00:12:01,850 --> 00:12:11,294
So, okay, I've got to work with it, which means the next time it arises, being slightly on the ball, just waiting for that energy to dissipate, dissipate, dissipate.

113
00:12:11,544 --> 00:12:13,826
Now that energy, remember, doesn't disappear.

114
00:12:14,268 --> 00:12:16,909
It's always transforming to its opposite.

115
00:12:17,009 --> 00:12:20,133
So where there was selfishness, they'll find generosity.

116
00:12:20,653 --> 00:12:22,936
Where there's hatred, you'll find love.

117
00:12:23,316 --> 00:12:28,500
And where there's cruelty, you'll find compassion and so on.

118
00:12:28,520 --> 00:12:32,904
So that was our little contemplation yesterday.

119
00:12:32,924 --> 00:12:40,692
It was probably slightly better, slightly longer yesterday, but at least we have

120
00:12:41,009 --> 00:13:05,042
gone over it again so it'll be slightly different from what you heard yesterday but at least we've covered the same area now i think i also said just to finally to finalize the to finish off uh this this moment of desire is actually the only moment of

121
00:13:05,258 --> 00:13:07,701
for want of a better word, free will, right?

122
00:13:07,740 --> 00:13:10,965
That's the point where we can actually say no or yes.

123
00:13:12,147 --> 00:13:15,811
Otherwise, we would just be automatons.

124
00:13:15,831 --> 00:13:18,595
We'd just be living faithfully.

125
00:13:18,875 --> 00:13:21,859
We wouldn't have an ability to guide ourselves.

126
00:13:22,659 --> 00:13:33,813
Now, when I say that's the moment of choice, the moment of free will, actually speaking, it's very narrow because what we want to do is get to a point of liberation from suffering.

127
00:13:34,232 --> 00:13:35,755
And the path is ahead of us.

128
00:13:36,376 --> 00:13:50,283
Now, we come along the path as if you were, so we say, just walking in the country, going somewhere to a tea shop, perhaps, of course, to a place where you can get a nice cup of coffee and a tea cake.

129
00:13:50,945 --> 00:13:52,006
And you know the way.

130
00:13:52,027 --> 00:13:52,849
It's on the map.

131
00:13:52,828 --> 00:13:56,152
And as you're going along, there's a little road to the left.

132
00:13:56,211 --> 00:13:57,972
And as you look, you think, oh, that's interesting.

133
00:13:58,533 --> 00:13:59,855
So now you've got a choice, you see.

134
00:13:59,914 --> 00:14:10,985
You can either wander up there, wasting time, getting more and more anxious as to whether the tea shop will be closed by the time you get there, and getting all flustered.

135
00:14:11,065 --> 00:14:14,168
And you may get lost, you see, even though you've got a map.

136
00:14:14,888 --> 00:14:18,130
And so you have to decide at that crossroad, have I got time?

137
00:14:18,171 --> 00:14:19,152
Do I want to go there?

138
00:14:19,172 --> 00:14:20,312
Do I need to go there?

139
00:14:21,014 --> 00:14:22,735
And then you move on.

140
00:14:22,715 --> 00:14:23,095
Right.

141
00:14:24,376 --> 00:14:43,659
So that that moment of choice when the desire comes up is the point where we can liberate ourselves, where we can actually make the decisions that will liberate ourselves from this whole process of desire.

142
00:14:45,765 --> 00:15:01,951
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and they have not caused even further confusion and that you will, by your devotion to practice, liberate yourself from all suffering sooner rather than later.

